Toxic Comment Detection System

Overview

This project is a Python-based system for detecting toxic online comments using multiple machine learning approaches.
It implements and compares three distinct models:

-BERT (bert-base-uncased) вЂ“ deep learning transformer model
-TF-IDF + OneVsRest Classifier вЂ“ traditional machine learning approach
-Rule-Based Model вЂ“ keyword/pattern-based classification

The system performs multi-label classification across six toxicity categories using real-world data from Kaggle.

---

Features

-Multi-label toxic comment classification
-Three independent modelling approaches
-Command-line interface for training and inference
-Shared evaluation pipeline across all models
-Real dataset integration from Kaggle

---

Labels Predicted

- toxic
- severe_toxic
- obscene
- threat
- insult
- identity_hate

---

Tech Stack

-Language: Python (Recommended: Python 3.13)
-Libraries:

  - pandas
  - numpy
  - scikit-learn
  - transformers
  - torch
  - nltk / regex
  - accelerate
  - matplotlib

---

Installation

1. Clone the repository

git clone https://github.com/JengaCube/BERT-Content-Moderation
cd BERT-Content-Moderation

2. Install dependencies

pip install -r requirements.txt

3. (Optional) Install PyTorch for BERT Training

If you plan to train the BERT model, it is strongly recommended to install PyTorch using the official selector:

https://pytorch.org/get-started/locally/

-Use CUDA for NVIDIA GPUs
-Use ROCm for AMD GPUs

This ensures optimal performance during training.

If you do not plan to train BERT or already have a trained model, you can install the CPU version:

pip install torch

---

4. Download dataset

Download the dataset manually from Kaggle:

https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/julian3833/jigsaw-toxic-comment-classification-challenge

5. Set up dataset directory

Place the CSV files in the following structure:

project-root/
в”‚в”Ђв”Ђ archive/
в”‚     в”њв”Ђв”Ђ train.csv
в”‚     в”њв”Ђв”Ђ test.csv
в”‚     в”њв”Ђв”Ђ test_labels.csv
в”‚в”Ђв”Ђ Preprocessing.py
в”‚в”Ђв”Ђ Fine-Tuning.py
в”‚в”Ђв”Ђ Usage.py
в”‚в”Ђв”Ђ TF-IDF FineTuning and usage.py
в”‚в”Ђв”Ђ Rule-Based.py
в”‚в”Ђв”Ђ Metrics.py

The archive folder must be in the same directory as the scripts.

How to Run

Step 1: Preprocess Data

python Preprocessing.py

This step prepares the dataset by:

- Removing links
- Removing IP addresses
- Cleaning raw text inputs

It is important that you run this first so that the Outputs directory is made

---

Choose a Model

Rule-Based Model

python Rule-Based.py

-No training required
-Uses keyword and pattern matching

---

TF-IDF Model (OneVsRest)

python "TF-IDF FineTuning and usage.py"

- Uses TF-IDF vectorisation
- Multi-label classification via OneVsRest

---

BERT Model (bert-base-uncased)

Train the model

python Fine-Tuning.py

- Fine-tunes BERT for multi-label classification
- Model is saved locally in:

SavedModel/Model/

Run evaluation / predictions

python Usage.py

---

User Input

You can input custom text directly through the terminal when running supported scripts:

Please enter your model prompt:

Example:

Input: "You are an idiot"
Output: toxic, insult

---

Evaluation Metrics

All models are evaluated using:

- Precision
- Recall
- F1-score
- False Positive Rate (FPR)
- Confusion Matrix

Example Output

